Imagine finding â€œIndiaâ€ in a book by reading every page until you find it.

ğŸ“— With Index:
You go to the index, find â€œIndia â†’ Page 240â€ and go directly there. Much faster.

ğŸ“‚ In Database Terms:
Table = Book

Row = Page

Index = Map that points to exact rows where data exists.

ğŸ—ï¸ How Indexing Works in a Database:
You create an index on a column (e.g., user_id, email, etc.).

Database builds a data structure (commonly B-Tree or Hash Table) behind the scenes.

When you run a query like:

sql
Copy
Edit
SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'abc@example.com';
â€” If email is indexed, the DB skips scanning all rows and goes directly to the match.

âš™ï¸ Types of Indexes:
| Index Type              | Use Case & Explanation                                                       |
| ----------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Single-column Index** | Indexes a single column.                                                     |
| **Composite Index**     | Indexes multiple columns together. Used when querying on multiple columns.   |
| **Unique Index**        | Ensures all values in the column are unique (e.g., emails, usernames).       |
| **Full-Text Index**     | For searching long text (like blog posts or descriptions).                   |
| **Hash Index**          | Uses hashing for faster exact-match lookups (good for key-value scenarios).  |
| **Bitmap Index**        | Efficient for columns with **low cardinality** (e.g., gender, status flags). |


ğŸ§  Pros of Indexing:
âœ… Fast read/search queries.

âœ… Improves performance on large tables.

âœ… Essential for JOINs and WHERE clauses.

âš ï¸ Cons of Indexing:
âŒ Slows down INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE operations (because index also needs to be updated).

âŒ Takes additional disk space.

âŒ Poor choice of columns can lead to no benefit or even worse performance.

